Step 1 — Go to AWS CodePipeline:

AWS Console
    ↓
Search: CodePipeline
    ↓
Click: Create pipeline

Select "Build custom pipeline" — that's the right option for your setup:   // note

Step 2 — Pipeline settings:

Pipeline name: aws-pipeline
Execution mode: Superseded
Service role: New service role (auto create)          // to this role only we add ploicy
    ↓
Click Next

Step 3 — Source stage:

Source provider: GitHub (Version 2)
    ↓
Click: Connect to GitHub
    ↓
Connection name: github-connection
Click: Connect to GitHub
Authorize AWS Connector
    ↓
Repository: kamalesh-parthiban/AWS-Pipeline
Branch: main
Output artifact: CodePipeline default
    ↓
Click Next

Step 4 — Build stage:

Build provider: AWS CodeBuild
Region: us-east-2
    ↓
Click: Create project (opens new tab)

    Project name: aws-pipeline-build
    
    Environment:
      Provisioning model: On-demand
      Environment image: Managed image
      OS: Ubuntu
      Runtime: Standard
      Image: aws/codebuild/standard:7.0
      Image version: Always use latest
      Service role: New service role
      ✅ Privileged mode: YES ← must tick this for Docker!
    
    Buildspec:
      Use a buildspec file ← auto reads buildspec.yml from repo  // we can even define here itself
    
    Logs:
      ✅ CloudWatch logs
      Group name: aws-pipeline-logs
    
    Click: Continue to CodePipeline ✅

Back in CodePipeline:
    ↓
Click Next

Step 5 — Deploy stage:

Click: Skip deploy stage
Confirm: Skip
    ↓
Click Next

Step 6 — Review:

Review everything
    ↓
Click: Create pipeline ✅

Step 7 — Add permissions to CodeBuild IAM role:

IAM → Roles
    ↓
Search: codebuild-aws-pipeline-build-service-role
    ↓
Add permissions → Attach policies:
    ✅ AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryFullAccess
    ✅ AmazonEKSClusterPolicy
    ✅ AmazonEKSWorkerNodePolicy
    ✅ CloudWatchLogsFullAccess
    ↓
Add inline policy:
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "eks:DescribeCluster",
        "eks:ListClusters"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
-----------------------------------
Step 8 — Add CodeBuild role to EKS:

# Run on your machine
kubectl edit configmap aws-auth -n kube-system

# Add under mapRoles section:
- rolearn: arn:aws:iam::382458445256:role/codebuild-aws-pipeline-build-service-role
  username: codebuild
  groups:
    - system:masters

$ kubectl get configmap aws-auth -n kube-system -o yaml
apiVersion: v1
data:
  mapRoles: |
    - rolearn: arn:aws:iam::382458445256:role/eks-node-role
      groups:
      - system:bootstrappers
      - system:nodes
      username: system:node:{{EC2PrivateDNSName}}
    - rolearn: arn:aws:iam::382458445256:role/codebuild-aws-pipeline-build-service-role            //add start
      username: codebuild
      groups:
      - system:masters                                                                              //add end
kind: ConfigMap


---------------------

Step 9 — Pipeline will auto trigger:

Pipeline triggers automatically on create
    ↓
Stage 1: Source ← pulls from GitHub ✅
    ↓
Stage 2: Build ← runs buildspec.yml
    ✅ Install kubectl
    ✅ Login ECR
    ✅ mvn build
    ✅ mvn test
    ✅ docker build
    ✅ push to ECR
    ✅ deploy to EKS
    ↓
Pods running 🎉

After pipeline succeeds verify:

# Check pods
kubectl get pods

# Check service
kubectl get svc pipeline-service

# Get URL
kubectl get svc pipeline-service \
  -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].hostname}'

# Test app
curl http://<EXTERNAL-IP>/
# Pipeline App is running! ✅

curl http://<EXTERNAL-IP>/health
